@oli-obk so I was re-reading the patch, but I feel like I don't quite get what you were saying about the revised evaluation strategy in [this comment](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/pull/30587#issuecomment-188711860). It seems to me that this strategy still ultimately relies on a type-hint -- can you spell out the scenario you were describing in a bit more detail maybe? Overall this PR looks really nice but I'm a bit concerned now that maybe I'm missing some subtle interplay around type-hints.

My feeling is that in order for constant evaluation to really be used deeply in type-check, we are going probably going to have to intertwine it better into collect, so that there is a back-and-forth between constant evaluation and typing. I'm not sure it's possible for them to be strictly separated.

In particular I want to make sure that we don't implicitly commit to "infinite precision" integers in constant evaluation and so forth. It seems to me that actually doing _any_ arithmetic on integer constants whose type is unknown is potentially committing to that, if we want to be strict about not doing constant eval that would trigger an overflow at runtime.

@oli-obk 

> ...Actual fallout from this PR in...

can you be more explicit about what the fallout was (what error? what line?) and why the change you suggested would fix it? I thought that change was all about getting a hint based on the declared argument types from a `const fn`, but in the file you linked, I don't see any `const fn` definitions?

> can you be more explicit about what the fallout was (what error? what line?) and why the change you suggested would fix it?

These failures are casts of paths (even worse, casts of paths that point outside of the current crate). The code to obtain a hint previously was

``` rust
let item_hint = if let UncheckedExprNoHint = ty_hint {
      match const_ty {
          Some(ty) => match ast_ty_to_prim_ty(tcx, ty) {
              Some(ty) => UncheckedExprHint(ty),
              None => UncheckedExprNoHint
          },
          None => UncheckedExprNoHint
      }
} else {
    ty_hint
};
```

which basically says "if there's no hint and typeck didn't finish yet, get a better hint". But when we do a cast, we insert a hint of the target type, so there's a hint, but it's different than the one of the constant definition we just evaluated. Basically this means that the type of a constant is ignored as long as the expression has a hint. This was wrong before my changes, but went by unnoticed.

I changed this to

``` rust
let item_hint = match const_ty {
    Some(ty) => match ast_ty_to_prim_ty(tcx, ty) {
        Some(ty) => ty_hint.checked_or(ty),
        None => ty_hint.erase_hint(),
    },
    None => ty_hint.erase_hint(),
};
```

which says, if there's a better type (e.g. because an assoc constant or a regular constant have a type (which they always do, but the current code can fail to produce a concrete type in some associated constant cases)), then we take the better type, and erase the type hint in case we have no information.

I'm not sure what's going on, but here's a breakdown of our current behavior (all tested on 64-bit, 32-bit might be more funky):

``` rust
let x: usize = std::u32::MAX as usize + 1; // fine on 64 bit
let x: usize = std::u64::MAX as usize + 1; // lint about adding with overflow + debug assertions triggered during runtime
let x: usize = 18446744073709551615; // fine on 64 bit (is u64::MAX)
let x: usize = 18446744073709551616; // error: int literal is too large (this is a hard error)
let x: u64 = 18446744073709551616; // error: int literal is too large (this is a hard error)
let x = 18446744073709551616u64; // error: int literal is too large (this is a hard error)

let y: u8 = 300; // lint about overflow, no debug assertions triggered during runtime

const X: usize = std::u32::MAX as usize + 1;
const Y: usize = std::u64::MAX as usize + 1;
let x: usize = X; // fine on 64 bit
let y: usize = Y; // error: attempted to add with overflow (this is a hard error)
```
